def generate_pipeline_expanded() -> List[Dict]:
    """Additional pipeline and technical behavior examples."""
    return [
        _c("How does DocWain detect document types?", "Document type detection uses multiple signals:\n\n1. **Structural patterns** — Section headers (\"Employment History\" = resume, \"Line Items\" = invoice)\n2. **Vocabulary distribution** — Legal terms (\"whereas\", \"indemnify\") vs medical terms (\"diagnosis\", \"prescribed\")\n3. **Entity distributions** — Monetary amounts suggest financial, medications suggest medical\n4. **Formatting conventions** — Tables with prices = invoice, bulleted skills = resume\n5. **Metadata** — File name hints, author field, creation date\n\nDetection happens automatically during the document understanding stage. I apply domain-specific extraction templates based on the detected type."),
        _c("What is the embedding model?", "DocWain uses **BAAI/bge-large-en-v1.5** for document embeddings:\n\n- **Dimensions:** 1024\n- **Type:** Dense sentence embeddings optimized for English retrieval\n- **Performance:** State-of-the-art on MTEB benchmark for retrieval tasks\n\nThe reranker is **BAAI/bge-reranker-base** (cross-encoder) which re-scores retrieved chunks for **15-25% accuracy improvement** over pure vector search.\n\nEmbeddings are cached in Redis with a local fallback for **40-60% latency reduction** on repeated queries."),
        _c("How does Redis caching work in DocWain?", "Redis serves multiple caching roles:\n\n| Cache Type | TTL | Purpose |\n|------------|-----|--------|\n| **Embedding cache** | 30 days | Avoid re-computing embeddings for similar queries |\n| **Session state** | 7 days | Conversation history per user session |\n| **Intelligence cache** | 30 days | Profile briefs and cross-doc analysis results |\n| **Query results** | Configurable | Repeated identical queries return cached answers |\n\nAll cache keys are **namespaced by profile**: `docwain:{subscription}:{profile}:*`. This prevents cross-profile cache pollution."),
        _c("How does the knowledge graph help DocWain?", "The optional **Neo4j knowledge graph** adds a relationship layer:\n\n- **Entity nodes** — People, organizations, dates, amounts, regulations extracted from documents\n- **Relationship edges** — `appears_in`, `relates_to`, `similar_to`, `works_at`, `employed_by`\n- **Multi-hop reasoning** — \"Who are the counterparties in contracts related to Project X?\" traverses entity chains\n- **Cross-document linking** — Same person appearing in a resume and a contract are automatically connected\n\nThe knowledge graph enriches retrieval by expanding query context with related entities, improving recall for complex analytical queries."),
        _c("What is correlation ID tracing?", "Every DocWain request gets a unique **UUID correlation ID** via middleware:\n\n- Generated at request entry (`CorrelationIdMiddleware`)\n- Included in all log entries for that request\n- Returned in the response headers\n- Enables **end-to-end tracing**: API entry → intent classification → retrieval → generation → response\n\nWhen debugging issues, the correlation ID lets you trace the complete lifecycle of any request across all services."),
        _c("How does DocWain handle streaming responses?", "Streaming is available via `POST /api/askStream`:\n\n- Uses **Server-Sent Events (SSE)** to deliver tokens as they're generated\n- Eliminates multi-second blank waits on complex queries\n- Client receives partial responses immediately\n- Metadata (sources, confidence) is sent after generation completes\n\nTeams responses don't use streaming — they show a processing card that updates when the full response is ready."),
        _c("What happens when two users query simultaneously?", "Concurrent queries are handled through:\n\n1. **FastAPI async** — Non-blocking request handling, each request independent\n2. **Profile isolation** — User A's query can't interfere with User B's\n3. **Redis-backed sessions** — Each session state is separate\n4. **LLM queue** — Ollama handles concurrent requests up to `LLM_MAX_CONCURRENCY` (default 8)\n5. **Timeout budgets** — Each stage has a time limit; exceeded requests return graceful errors\n\nUnder heavy load, the system queues requests rather than failing. Health endpoints report current load status."),
        _c("How does DocWain handle document updates?", "When a document is re-uploaded or updated:\n\n1. New version is extracted and chunked\n2. Old embeddings for that document are replaced (not appended)\n3. Deduplication prevents redundant chunks\n4. Intelligence (briefs, entities) is regenerated\n\nTo compare versions, upload both and ask: \"What changed between v1 and v2?\" — I'll identify additions, removals, and modifications."),
        _c("What is the answerability index?", "The **answerability index** tracks what questions can be answered from each document:\n\n- During extraction, DocWain generates a taxonomy of ~32 query types per document\n- For each type, it records whether the document contains sufficient evidence\n- When you ask a question, the index helps quickly filter to answerable documents\n- Reduces retrieval noise by excluding documents that definitely can't answer the query\n\nThis improves both speed and accuracy — fewer irrelevant chunks means better answers."),
        _c("How do I monitor DocWain's performance?", "DocWain provides several monitoring endpoints:\n\n- **`GET /api/health`** — Basic API health status\n- **`GET /api/health/ready`** — Readiness probe (checks Qdrant, Redis, Ollama)\n- **`GET /api/metrics`** — Aggregate performance metrics with date filtering\n- **`GET /api/debug`** — Diagnostic information\n\nStructured JSON logging with correlation IDs enables integration with monitoring tools (Azure Monitor, ELK, Grafana). Every request logs query time, retrieval time, generation time, and confidence scores."),
    ]


